es:\n- Current user and database\n- System and database-level authorization (auth::Level::NONE, RO, RW)\n- Admin status and roles\n- JWT token\n\nKey static methods:\n- `current()` - Returns the current thread-local execution context\n- `superuser()` - Returns an internal superuser context\n- `create()` - Creates an ExecContext for a given user/database, checking permissions via UserManager\n\n## 4. User Management REST Endpoint\n\n**arangod/RestHandler/RestUsersHandler.h** and **arangod/RestHandler/RestUsersHandler.cpp** implement the `RestUsersHandler` class which handles the `/_api/user` REST endpoint. Methods include:\n- `getRequest()` - Retrieve user information\n- `postRequest()` - Create new users\n- `putRequest()` - Update user passwords\n- `patchRequest()` - Modify user properties\n- `deleteRequest()` - Remove users\n\n## 5. Default Authentication Settings\n\n**arangod/GeneralServer/AuthenticationOptions.h** defines `AuthenticationOptions` struct with defaults:\n- `active = true` - Authentication enabled by default\n- `authenticationSystemOnly = true` - Enforce auth on system database\n- `authenticationUnixSockets = true` - Enforce auth on Unix sockets\n- `sessionTimeout = 3600.0` - 1 hour default session timeout\n- `minimalJwtExpiryTime = 10.0` - 10 seconds minimum\n- `maximalJwtExpiryTime = 3600.0` - 1 hour maximum\n\n**arangod/GeneralServer/AuthenticationFeature.h** and **arangod/GeneralServer/AuthenticationFeature.cpp** manage authentication startup and configuration. Key methods:\n- `collectOptions()` - Registers command-line options like `--server.authentication`, `--server.session-timeout`, `--server.authentication-timeout`\n- `loadJwtSecretsFromFile()` - Load JWT signing keys\n- `jwtSecrets()` - Retrieve active and passive JWT secrets\n\n## 6. REST Authentication Handler\n\n**arangod/RestHandler/RestAuthHandler.h** and **arangod/RestHandler/RestAuthHandler.cpp** implement the `RestAuthHandler` class which handles the `/_open/auth` endpoint for JWT generation. It includes the `generateJwt()` method that creates signed JWT tokens for authenticated users.\n\n## Authentication Flow\n\n1. REST requests are authenticated via `TokenCache::checkAuthentication()` in the HTTP handler layer\n2. For JWT: Token is parsed and validated via `checkAuthenticationJWT()`, checking signature and expiry\n3. For Basic auth: Credentials are checked against UserManager\n4. An `ExecContext` is created with the authenticated user's permissions\n5. Database operations use the ExecContext to enforce authorization via UserManager's permission checks\n6. The `/_api/user` endpoint allows administrators to manage users and permissions"
